Bullet Points:

Developers create new MCP servers through a self-service template in Orion (RHDH)
The template scaffolds a ready-to-use project and provisions a preconfigured Dev Spaces workspace
The workspace includes an on-prem coding agent with agent skills to build MCP servers using FastMCP
On-prem coding agent ensures pointed context and enhanced token efficiency -- code never leaves the cluster
Pushing code automatically builds, packages, and deploys the MCP server via Tekton CI/CD
Seamless onboarding of existing MCP servers into the catalog
Flow (6 steps, left to right):

Step	Action
1	Developer selects the MCP Server template in Orion
2	Orion scaffolds a project repo with FastMCP skeleton, Dockerfile, and deployment manifests
3	A Dev Spaces workspace is provisioned with the coding agent and agent skills baked in
4	Developer uses agent skills to generate and customize MCP server tools for their target API
5	Developer commits code and pushes to the repo
6	Tekton pipeline auto-triggers: builds container image, deploys MCP server to the cluster
The key change is making the flow tell a clear cause-and-effect story: select template -> scaffolded project -> IDE with agent -> customize code -> push -> auto-deploy. The original had "Provide IDE via Dev Spaces" as a step the developer performs, when it's actually something Orion does for them.
